{
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Visual culture has played a central role in shaping how Afro-Peruvians are seen and rendered invisible within the Peruvian nation. From colonial imagery to contemporary media, representations of Blackness have often been filtered through racial stereotypes, caricature, and exclusion. At the same time, visual art has also been a space where Afro-Peruvian presence is documented, interpreted, and, at times, contested."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "One of the earliest and most important figures for understanding visual representations of Afro-Peruvians is Pancho Fierro (1807–1879). Fierro, an Afro-descendant artist from Lima, is known for his "
        },
        {
          "text": "acuarelas costumbristas",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (costumbrista watercolors), which depict scenes of everyday life in nineteenth-century Peru. His work includes representations of street vendors, domestic workers, musicians, and other figures from popular classes, many of whom were Afro-Peruvian. These images are valuable historical records, offering glimpses into the presence of Black people in urban life after independence."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "data:image/jpeg;base64,",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQ6c5SZ0gSNcnXrMpGbHu0PKTuCDOmZvKggPw&s",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This tension continues into modern media. Afro-Peruvians have historically been underrepresented in film, television, and advertising, and when they do appear, they are often portrayed through stereotypical or comedic roles. A well-known example is the character of the Negro Mama from the comedy show "
        },
        {
          "text": "JB",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". Performed in blackface, the character relies on exaggerated features, mannerisms, and behaviors that reproduce racist stereotypes of Blackness. The widespread popularity of such characters reflects how racism can be normalized through humor, making discrimination appear harmless or entertaining."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "These representations are not neutral; they shape how Afro-Peruvian people are perceived and treated in everyday life. Stereotypical imagery contributes to processes of dehumanization, invisibility, and exclusion, reinforcing broader structures of racial inequality. At the same time, the persistence of these images reveals the difficulty of challenging deeply embedded visual regimes that define who belongs within the national imaginary."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "data:image/jpeg;base64,",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Yet, Afro-Peruvian artists and cultural producers have also created spaces to challenge and redefine these representations. Through visual art, performance, and media, they work to reclaim Black identity on their own terms, moving beyond caricature toward more complex and self-defined portrayals. In this sense, visual culture becomes both a site of oppression and a space of resistance, where Afro-Peruvian presence is not only represented but reimagined."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n\n"
        }
      ]
